&lt;p&gt;Which of the following will form a heterogeneous mixture with each other?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(i) common salt&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(ii) sand&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(iii) water&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(iv) lemon juice&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;options (ii) and (iv)&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Concept:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Mixtures:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A mixture is a substance that consists of two or more elements or compounds &lt;strong&gt;not chemically combined together.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For Example - Air is a mixture of gases like oxygen, nitrogen, argon, CO&lt;span style=&quot; line-height: 0; position: relative; vertical-align: baseline; bottom: -0.25em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;, and water vapour.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Types of Mixtures:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Homogeneous Mixture:&lt;/span&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Those mixtures, in which the substances are completely mixed together and are indistinguishable from one another, are called homogeneous mixtures.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example Soda water, Soft drinks, lemonade, salt or sugar solution, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Heterogeneous Mixture:&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Those mixtures in which the substances remain separate and one substance is spread throughout the other substance as small particles, droplets, or bubbles are called heterogeneous mixtures.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;All the suspensions and colloids are heterogeneous mixtures.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For Example: - Sugar and sand mixture, muddy river water, soap solution.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;1&quot; cellspacing=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot; width: 350px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Common salt + lemon juice&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Homogeneous mixture&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Sand + lemon juice&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Heterogeneous mixture&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;water + lemon juice&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Homogeneous mixture&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Common salt + water&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Homogeneous mixture&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concept&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;-&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hormones &lt;/strong&gt;are non-nutrient chemicals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A physical change occurs in the body by certain chemical substances are called &lt;strong&gt;hormones&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;hormone &lt;/strong&gt;is secreted by the endocrine glands into the blood.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Explanation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;-&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;//storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/22/02/61a9ad14741e848884543e6b_16454363202991.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;hypothalamus &lt;/strong&gt;is the basal part of the diencephalon, forebrain&amp;nbsp;and it regulates a wide spectrum of body functions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hypothalamus &lt;/strong&gt;regulates the synthesis and secretion of &lt;strong&gt;pituitary hormones.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The hormones produced by the &lt;strong&gt;hypothalamus &lt;/strong&gt;are of two types, the &lt;strong&gt;releasing hormones&lt;/strong&gt; (which stimulate secretion of pituitary hormones) and the inhibiting hormones.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For example, a hypothalamic hormone called &lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Gonadotrophin&lt;/span&gt; releasing hormone (GnRH) stimulates the pituitary synthesis and release of gonadotropins.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The hypothalamus releases &lt;strong&gt;growth hormone-releasing factor(GHRF)&lt;/strong&gt; the anterior pituitary is stimulated to release &lt;strong&gt;growth hormone (GH).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore h&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;ypothalamus&amp;nbsp;releases growth hormone-releasing factor which stimulates the pituitary gland to release growth hormone.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;Adrenal gland&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Our body has one pair of adrenal glands, one at the anterior part of each kidney.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The gland is composed of two types of tissues.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The centrally located tissue is called the adrenal medulla, and outside this lies the adrenal cortex.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Pancreas&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The pancreas is a composite gland that acts as both exocrine and endocrine glands.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The endocrine pancreas consists of &amp;lsquo;Islets of Langerhans&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There are about 1 to 2 million Islets of Langerhans in a normal human pancreas representing only 1 to 2 per cent of the pancreatic tissue.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Ovaries&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Females have a pair of ovaries located in the abdomen.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The ovary is the primary female sex organ that produces one ovum during each menstrual cycle.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In addition, the ovary also produces two groups of steroid hormones called estrogen and progesterone.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;They are neutral.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Neutrons are subatomic particles&lt;/strong&gt; found in the nucleus of an atom alongside protons.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They have &lt;strong&gt;no electrical charge&lt;/strong&gt;, which means they are neutral. &lt;em&gt;Hence, the statement &amp;quot;They are neutral&amp;quot; is correct.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;mass of a neutron&lt;/strong&gt; is slightly higher than that of a proton but the difference is minimal. &lt;em&gt;The statement &amp;quot;They are heavier than protons&amp;quot; is correct but not as relevant as their neutrality here.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Neutrons do not carry a &lt;strong&gt;positive or negative charge&lt;/strong&gt;, unlike protons (positive) and electrons (negative). &lt;em&gt;The statements &amp;quot;They have positive charge&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;They have negative charge&amp;quot; are incorrect.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Neutrons, along with protons, contribute significantly to the &lt;strong&gt;atomic mass&lt;/strong&gt; of an element.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Protons, Neutrons, and Electrons:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Atoms are composed of three primary subatomic particles: &lt;strong&gt;protons, neutrons, and electrons&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Protons carry a &lt;strong&gt;positive charge&lt;/strong&gt;, electrons carry a &lt;strong&gt;negative charge&lt;/strong&gt;, and neutrons are &lt;strong&gt;neutral&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The number of protons defines the &lt;strong&gt;atomic number&lt;/strong&gt;, while the sum of protons and neutrons gives the atomic mass.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Discovery of Neutrons:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Neutrons were discovered by &lt;strong&gt;James Chadwick in 1932&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;His experiments involved bombarding beryllium with alpha particles, resulting in the emission of neutral particles.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Role of Neutrons:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Neutrons help to stabilize the nucleus by reducing the &lt;strong&gt;electrostatic repulsion&lt;/strong&gt; between protons.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They play a crucial role in &lt;strong&gt;nuclear reactions&lt;/strong&gt;, such as fission and fusion.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Neutrons determine the &lt;strong&gt;isotopes&lt;/strong&gt; of an element. For example, carbon-12 and carbon-14 are isotopes of carbon with different neutron numbers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Neutrons:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Neutrons are used in &lt;strong&gt;neutron scattering experiments&lt;/strong&gt; to study the structure of materials.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are essential in &lt;strong&gt;nuclear reactors&lt;/strong&gt; for initiating and sustaining fission reactions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Neutron imaging is used in &lt;strong&gt;non-destructive testing&lt;/strong&gt; for analyzing internal structures of objects.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Important Facts:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The mass of a neutron is approximately &lt;strong&gt;1.675 &amp;times; 10&lt;sup&gt;-27&lt;/sup&gt; kg&lt;/strong&gt;, slightly more than a proton.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Neutrons have a &lt;strong&gt;mean lifetime of about 14 minutes and 42 seconds&lt;/strong&gt; outside the nucleus before decaying into a proton, an electron, and an antineutrino.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Atomic Stability:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Neutrons play an essential role in maintaining the &lt;strong&gt;stability of the atomic nucleus&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Without neutrons, the nucleus would be unstable due to the repulsion between positively charged protons.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Isotopes and Nuclear Forces:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Isotopes of an element differ in their number of neutrons, not protons or electrons. For instance, hydrogen has three isotopes: &lt;strong&gt;protium, deuterium, and tritium&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Neutrons mediate the &lt;strong&gt;nuclear strong force&lt;/strong&gt;, which binds protons and neutrons together in the nucleus.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iron&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;57&quot; data-start=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;284&quot; data-start=&quot;78&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iron&lt;/strong&gt; is used as a &lt;strong&gt;catalyst&lt;/strong&gt; in the &lt;strong&gt;Haber process&lt;/strong&gt;, which is employed for the synthesis of ammonia from nitrogen and hydrogen gases.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;605&quot; data-start=&quot;482&quot;&gt;The catalyst is typically promoted with small amounts of other substances, such as &lt;strong&gt;potassium and aluminum oxides&lt;/strong&gt;, to enhance its efficiency.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;692&quot; data-start=&quot;610&quot;&gt;Iron serves as a surface where the &lt;strong&gt;adsorption&lt;/strong&gt; of nitrogen (N&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;) and hydrogen (H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;) molecules occurs, facilitating the breaking of strong triple bonds in nitrogen molecules. &lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, it is ideal for this process.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1041&quot; data-start=&quot;850&quot;&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Haber process&lt;/strong&gt; operates at high temperatures (400&amp;ndash;500&amp;deg;C) and pressures (150&amp;ndash;200 atm) to achieve high reaction rates. Iron remains effective under such conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1162&quot; data-start=&quot;1046&quot;&gt;Other metals such as &lt;strong&gt;platinum, nickel, and copper&lt;/strong&gt; are not used for the Haber process as they are either less effective or too expensive. &lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;Hence, they are not suitable for this process.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;1999&quot; data-start=&quot;1809&quot;&gt;The use of iron as a catalyst in the Haber process revolutionized the production of ammonia, which is a critical ingredient in fertilizers and other industrial chemicals. &lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;This makes the process economically viable.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;2112&quot; data-start=&quot;2076&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Iron&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Haber Process:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2410&quot; data-start=&quot;2195&quot;&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Haber process&lt;/strong&gt; was developed by the German chemist &lt;strong&gt;Fritz Haber&lt;/strong&gt; in the early 20th century and later industrialized by Carl Bosch.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2684&quot; data-start=&quot;2415&quot;&gt;It is a method for producing &lt;strong&gt;ammonia&lt;/strong&gt; (NH&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;) by combining nitrogen (N&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;) from the air with hydrogen (H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;), typically derived from natural gas.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;2860&quot; data-start=&quot;2735&quot;&gt;The reaction is represented as: &lt;strong&gt;N&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; + 3H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; ⇌ 2NH&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, which is exothermic.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Role of Catalysts in the Haber Process:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3071&quot; data-start=&quot;2865&quot;&gt;Catalysts like &lt;strong&gt;iron&lt;/strong&gt; help lower the activation energy required for the reaction, increasing the rate of ammonia production.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3250&quot; data-start=&quot;3076&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Promoters&lt;/strong&gt; such as potassium oxide improve the efficiency and durability of the iron catalyst.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Ammonia:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3402&quot; data-start=&quot;3301&quot;&gt;Ammonia is used in the production of &lt;strong&gt;fertilizers&lt;/strong&gt;, such as urea and ammonium nitrate, which are essential for agriculture.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;3580&quot; data-start=&quot;3407&quot;&gt;It is also used as a &lt;strong&gt;refrigerant&lt;/strong&gt;, in the manufacture of explosives, and in the production of cleaning agents.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Iron as a Catalyst:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4636&quot; data-start=&quot;4411&quot;&gt;Iron is preferred due to its &lt;strong&gt;availability, cost-effectiveness, and ability to function under high temperatures and pressures&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;4761&quot; data-start=&quot;4641&quot;&gt;Despite being effective, the iron catalyst slowly deactivates over time due to sintering and poisoning by impurities like sulfur.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alternative Catalysts:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5043&quot; data-start=&quot;4817&quot;&gt;Platinum and nickel are sometimes used in laboratory-scale ammonia synthesis, but their &lt;strong&gt;high cost&lt;/strong&gt; makes them unsuitable for industrial use.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;5259&quot; data-start=&quot;5048&quot;&gt;Copper is generally not used in the Haber process but serves as a catalyst in other reactions, such as the oxidation of ammonia.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Colour of a substance&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A thermometric property is any physical property that changes measurably with temperature and can be used for temperature measurement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Colour of a substance&lt;/strong&gt; is not considered a thermometric property as it does not have a predictable or consistent relationship with temperature for accurate measurement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Examples of thermometric properties include &lt;strong&gt;pressure, volume, length, electrical resistance, and thermal expansion&lt;/strong&gt;, which are commonly used in various thermometers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Properties such as pressure and electrical resistance are widely applied in devices like gas thermometers and resistance temperature detectors (RTDs).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Colour changes with temperature (e.g., in some materials) are not precise enough to serve as a reliable thermometric property in practical applications.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thermometric Properties:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These are physical properties of matter that change in a predictable and measurable way with temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include thermal expansion (length or volume), pressure of a gas, and electrical resistance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These properties are utilized in designing instruments like thermometers and pyrometers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Common Thermometers:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mercury-in-glass thermometers use the expansion of mercury as a thermometric property.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Resistance thermometers (RTDs) use the change in electrical resistance of a conductor.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Gas thermometers rely on the pressure of a fixed volume of gas as the thermometric property.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Why Colour is Not a Thermometric Property:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;While some materials change colour with temperature (e.g., thermochromic materials), the change is not consistent or linear across all substances.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Colour changes are not easily quantifiable in a manner suitable for precise temperature measurement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Thermometric Properties:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Thermometric properties are used in both scientific and industrial settings for accurate temperature monitoring and control.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include clinical thermometers, industrial sensors, and meteorological equipment.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Length over time&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The speed limit on a highway is a measure of &lt;strong&gt;velocity or speed&lt;/strong&gt;, which is defined as the rate of change of position with time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The dimensional formula for speed is &lt;strong&gt;Length/Time&lt;/strong&gt;, represented as [L T⁻&amp;sup1;] in terms of fundamental physical quantities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Speed is a scalar quantity, meaning it has magnitude but no direction, unlike velocity, which is a vector.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the context of highways, speed limits are usually expressed in units such as &lt;strong&gt;kilometers per hour (km/h)&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;miles per hour (mph)&lt;/strong&gt;, both of which align with the dimension of length over time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct dimensional understanding of speed is essential for applications in traffic regulations, transportation engineering, and physics.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Speed vs Velocity:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Speed&lt;/strong&gt; is a scalar quantity, while &lt;strong&gt;velocity&lt;/strong&gt; is a vector quantity (includes both magnitude and direction).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Both have the same dimensional formula [L T⁻&amp;sup1;], but velocity accounts for direction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Common Units of Speed:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;SI Unit: &lt;strong&gt;meters per second (m/s)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Other Units: &lt;strong&gt;kilometers per hour (km/h), miles per hour (mph), or knots&lt;/strong&gt; (used in aviation and maritime).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dimensional Analysis:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Dimensional analysis helps verify equations or convert units by ensuring consistent dimensions across physical quantities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For speed, the dimension is derived from distance (length) divided by time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Practical Applications of Speed:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used in transportation to set speed limits for safety and efficiency.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Plays a critical role in physics, engineering, and sports science.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Smallest surface area for a given volume&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The spherical nature of water and oil drops is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot; &quot;&gt;due to the phenomena of surface tension.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On smaller raindrops, the surface tension is stronger than in larger drops.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For a given volume of a liquid, a sphere has the least surface area.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The more the surface area of an object, the more is its surface energy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Surface tension&lt;/strong&gt; in water might be good at performing tricks, such as being able to float a paper clip on its surface, but surface tension performs many more duties that are vitally important to the environment and people.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The cohesive forces between liquid molecules are responsible for the phenomenon known as surface tension.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Genetics&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Genetics&lt;/strong&gt; is the branch of biology that studies &lt;strong&gt;heredity&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;variation&lt;/strong&gt; in organisms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Heredity refers to the process by which traits and characteristics are passed down from &lt;strong&gt;parents to their offspring&lt;/strong&gt; through genes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Variation is the differences in traits among individuals of the same species, which occur due to genetic and environmental factors.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The term &amp;quot;Genetics&amp;quot; was coined by &lt;strong&gt;William Bateson&lt;/strong&gt; in &lt;strong&gt;1905&lt;/strong&gt;, who is regarded as one of the pioneers in the field.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Genetics plays a vital role in understanding &lt;strong&gt;inheritance patterns&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;genetic disorders&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;evolutionary biology&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;biotechnology&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Evolution:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Evolution is the process through which organisms change over time due to &lt;strong&gt;natural selection&lt;/strong&gt;, mutations, and genetic drift.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It explains how species adapt to their environments and how new species emerge from existing ones.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This concept was famously proposed by &lt;strong&gt;Charles Darwin&lt;/strong&gt; in his book &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;On the Origin of Species&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; published in &lt;strong&gt;1859&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mutation:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A mutation is a change in the DNA sequence of an organism&amp;#39;s genome.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Mutations can occur naturally or due to external factors like &lt;strong&gt;radiation&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;chemical exposure&lt;/strong&gt;, or &lt;strong&gt;errors in DNA replication&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are a significant source of genetic variation, which is crucial for evolution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Biology:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Biology is the study of living organisms, including their structure, function, growth, evolution, and distribution.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It encompasses various subfields like &lt;strong&gt;botany&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;zoology&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;ecology&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;genetics&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The study of biology contributes to advancements in medicine, agriculture, conservation, and biotechnology.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Genetics in Application:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gregor Mendel&lt;/strong&gt;, known as the &amp;quot;Father of Genetics,&amp;quot; conducted pioneering experiments on pea plants to understand heredity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Genetics is applied in fields like &lt;strong&gt;medical research&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;genetic engineering&lt;/strong&gt;, &lt;strong&gt;agriculture&lt;/strong&gt;, and &lt;strong&gt;forensic science&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example, genetically modified crops are produced using principles of genetics to enhance yield and resistance to pests.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Concepts in Genetics:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DNA (Deoxyribonucleic Acid)&lt;/strong&gt; is the molecule that carries genetic information in most organisms.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Genes&lt;/strong&gt; are specific sequences of DNA that code for proteins and determine traits.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chromosomes&lt;/strong&gt; are structures within cells that contain DNA. Humans have &lt;strong&gt;23 pairs of chromosomes&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Genetic Disorders&lt;/strong&gt; like &lt;strong&gt;Sickle Cell Anemia&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Cystic Fibrosis&lt;/strong&gt; are caused by mutations in specific genes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Advancements in &lt;strong&gt;genomics&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;CRISPR technology&lt;/strong&gt; have revolutionized genetic research and therapy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cl2 + H2O &amp;rarr; HCI + HOCI&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Disproportionation reactions involve the simultaneous oxidation and reduction of the same species within a chemical reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the reaction &lt;strong&gt;Cl₂ + H₂O &amp;rarr; HCl + HOCl&lt;/strong&gt;, chlorine (Cl₂) undergoes disproportionation as it is both oxidized to form hypochlorous acid (HOCl) and reduced to form hydrochloric acid (HCl).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The oxidation state of chlorine in Cl₂ is 0. In HCl, it is reduced to -1, and in HOCl, it is oxidized to +1.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This reaction occurs naturally in water when chlorine is dissolved, and is often used in water purification and disinfection processes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Disproportionation reactions are a subset of redox reactions and are characterized by the same element undergoing both gain and loss of electrons.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oxidation:&lt;/strong&gt; It refers to the loss of electrons or an increase in oxidation state during a chemical reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reduction:&lt;/strong&gt; Reduction is the gain of electrons or a decrease in oxidation state during a chemical reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oxidation State:&lt;/strong&gt; It is a number assigned to an element in a compound or ion that represents the number of electrons lost (positive oxidation state) or gained (negative oxidation state).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Redox Reactions:&lt;/strong&gt; These are reactions in which oxidation and reduction occur simultaneously, involving the transfer of electrons between species.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Disproportionation Reactions:&lt;/strong&gt; Such reactions are widely used in industrial processes, water treatment, and chemical synthesis (e.g., the production of bleaching agents and disinfectants).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;High pressure.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Divers wear special suits in order to protect them from&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;High pressure.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;pressure increases as the&amp;nbsp;depth increase.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The pressure exerted in deep water&amp;nbsp;under the sea is much greater than at the sea level.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So divers need a proper suit to bear that extra pressure.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
